<chapter xml:id="vector-calculus" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Vector Calculus</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this chapter, we reach the culmination of our work in <xref first="vectors-space-geometry" last="multiple-integrals" text="global">Chapters</xref>, obtaining a unified picture of calculus in higher dimensions.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <section xml:id="section-vector-fields">
    <title>Vector Fields</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Consider the function <m>f(x,y) = \frac{1}{2}(x^{2} + y^{2})</m>.
        The gradient of this function is <m>\grad f = \dotprod{-y, x}</m>.
        We can view the gradient as a <em>function</em> that assigns the vector <m>\grad f(x,y)</m> to each point <m>(x,y)</m> in the plane.
        <figure xml:id="figure-the-gradient-field-for--grad-f-">
          <caption>The gradient field for <m>\grad f</m></caption>
          <image xml:id="image-the-gradient-field-for--grad-f-">
            <asymptote>
              import graph;
              import slopefield;
              import fontsize;
              defaultpen(fontsize(9pt));
              size(200);
              real xmin=-2.1, xmax=2.1;
              real ymin=-2.1, ymax=2.1;

              //hopefully changes vectorfield settings...
              picture vectorfield(path vector(real), path g, int n, bool truesize=false,
                    pen p=currentpen, arrowbar arrow=Arrow(TeXHead));

              pair a=(-2,-2);
              pair b=(2,2);

              //Define gradient field
              path vector(pair z) {return (0,0)--(z.x,z.y);}

              add(vectorfield(vector,a,b,deepblue+1bp));

              xaxis("$x$",YEquals(0),xmin,xmax,LeftTicks(),arrow=Arrow(TeXHead));
              //xaxis(YEquals(ymax),xmin,xmax);
              yaxis("$y$",XEquals(0),ymin,ymax,RightTicks());
              //yaxis(XEquals(xmax),ymin,ymax);

              attach(legend(),point(E),20E,UnFill);
            </asymptote>
          </image>
        </figure>
        Such functions are the main object of this section.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <definition xml:id="definition-vector-fields">
      <idx><h>vector fields</h></idx>
      <title>Vector Fields</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>vector field</term> is a function <m>\vv{F}</m> that assigns vectors to points.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      A vector field on <m>\RR^{2}</m> would look like
      <me>\vv{F}(x,y) = \dotprod{P(x,y), Q(x,y)} = P(x,y)\vv{i} + Q(x,y)\vv{j} = P\vv{i} + Q\vv{j}</me>.
    </p>
  </section>
</chapter>
